# Step 1: Select only the relevant columns
data = data[['BLDG_ID', 'YEAR_BUILT', 'SHAPE_AREA', 'geometry']]

# Step 2: Data Cleaning
# Drop rows with missing values in the selected columns
data = data.dropna(subset=['BLDG_ID', 'YEAR_BUILT', 'SHAPE_AREA'])

# Ensure YEAR_BUILT is an integer (convert if necessary)
data['YEAR_BUILT'] = data['YEAR_BUILT'].astype(int)

# Remove duplicate rows based on 'BLDG_ID'
data = data.drop_duplicates(subset='BLDG_ID')

# Optional: Remove unrealistic values
# Assuming buildings should have positive area and plausible year (e.g., 1800 onwards)
data = data[(data['YEAR_BUILT'] >= 1800) & (data['SHAPE_AREA'] > 0)]

# Check the cleaned data
print(data.head())
print(f"Number of rows after cleaning: {len(data)}")

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# Filter the dataset for buildings with YEAR_BUILT > 1920, STORIES > 30, and SHAPE_AREA is valid
data_filtered = data[(data['YEAR_BUILT'] > 1920) & (data['STORIES'] > 30) & data['SHAPE_AREA'].notna()]

# Determine sample size based on the available data
sample_size = min(5000, len(data_filtered))  # Take 5000 samples or fewer if data has less than 5000 rows

# Sample random rows from the filtered dataset
sample_data = data_filtered.sample(n=sample_size, random_state=1)

# Normalize the STORIES column for the color gradient
normalized_stories = (sample_data['STORIES'] - sample_data['STORIES'].min()) / (sample_data['STORIES'].max() - sample_data['STORIES'].min())
colors = plt.cm.Reds(normalized_stories)  # Use a red gradient for the color hue

# Create a bar plot with YEAR_BUILT on the x-axis and SHAPE_AREA on the y-axis
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
plt.bar(sample_data['YEAR_BUILT'], sample_data['SHAPE_AREA'], color=colors, edgecolor='black')
plt.xlabel('Year Built')
plt.ylabel('Shape Area (sf)')
plt.title('Chicago Building Shape Area by Year Built (Sampled, Stories > 30, Year > 1920)', fontsize=16)
plt.xticks(rotation=45)  # Rotate x-axis labels for better readability
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from wordcloud import WordCloud

# Prepare the text data from 'CREATE_USE'
text_data = ' '.join(data2['CREATE_USE'].dropna().astype(str).values)

# Generate the word cloud
wordcloud = WordCloud(
    width=800, 
    height=400,
    background_color='white',
    colormap='Reds',  # Use the same color hue
    max_words=300,
    random_state=42
).generate(text_data)

# Plot the word cloud
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.imshow(wordcloud, interpolation='bilinear')
plt.axis('off')  # Remove axes for better visualization
plt.title('Word Cloud of Building Functions (CREATE_USE)', fontsize=18)

# Filter data for buildings with stories > 30 and built after 1920

    (data2['STORIES'] > 30) &
    (data2['YEAR_BUILT'] > 1920)
]

# Drop rows with missing values in relevant columns

# Sort by the number of stories in descending order

)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# Filter data for buildings with stories > 30 and built after 1920
filtered_data = data2[
    (data2['STORIES'] > 30) &
    (data2['YEAR_BUILT'] > 1920)
]

# Drop rows with missing values in relevant columns
filtered_data = filtered_data.dropna(subset=['BLDG_NAME1', 'STORIES', 'YEAR_BUILT'])

# Sort by the number of stories in descending order and select top 20
top_buildings = filtered_data.nlargest(20, 'STORIES')

# Combine relevant information into a new column for display
top_buildings['Info'] = (
    top_buildings['BLDG_NAME1'] + "\n" +
    "Year Built: " + top_buildings['YEAR_BUILT'].astype(str)
)

# Normalize the number of stories for color intensity
normalized_stories = (top_buildings['STORIES'] - top_buildings['STORIES'].min()) / (top_buildings['STORIES'].max() - top_buildings['STORIES'].min())
colors = plt.cm.Reds(normalized_stories)

# Plot the bar chart
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
plt.barh(top_buildings['Info'], top_buildings['STORIES'], color=colors, edgecolor='black')
plt.xlabel('Number of Stories', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Buildings', fontsize=12)
plt.title('Top 20 Tallest Buildings by Stories (Year > 1920, Stories > 30)', fontsize=16)
plt.gca().invert_yaxis()  # Ensure the tallest building is on top
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
